{
  "card_id": "wick_formation",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Wick Formation",
  "aliases": [
    "Candle Wick",
    "Letting the Wick Form",
    "letting the wick form",
    "Opposing Run",
    "Shadow"
  ],
  "school": "Price Action",
  "definition": "A candlestick's upper or lower shadow representing opposing price movement before the close. Small wicks formed early in the period support expansion in the body's direction; large wicks signal reversal candles that return toward the opening price. The opposing run, when price closes back through the series of opposing candles, creates an order block or protected swing at the wick's extreme.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Determine the anticipated directional bias (bullish or bearish) based on higher time frame structure or session direction.",
    "Evaluate wick size: a small wick relative to the body formed early in the period supports an expansion candle; a large wick or prolonged opposing run consuming most of the range indicates a reversal candle.",
    "In an expansion candle, price opens, forms a shallow opposing wick early (lower wick for bullish, upper wick for bearish), then trends in the bias direction and closes near the high/low.",
    "The opposing run should engage a point of interest such as a prior order block, fair value gap, premium/discount zone, or equilibrium of the prior range.",
    "The wick is validated when price closes back through the opposing candle series (change in state of delivery), establishing a protected swing or order block.",
    "Once validated, the extreme of the wick serves as the invalidation point and should not be taken out if the bias is correct.",
    "On lower time frames, use a fractal model (CISD + protected swing aligned with the higher time frame bias) to confirm wick completion before entering in the higher time frame direction."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Wait for the wick to form, using wick size as the primary filter. Shallow wicks signal continuation and expansion, allowing entry on the same or next candle with stops at the wick's extreme and targets toward standard deviation or prior day levels. Large wicks indicate a reversal candle and require waiting for the next higher time frame candle to open before trading. Entry is best confirmed on candle 3 after a small wick. Align multiple time frames showing small wicks for higher probability. Use the validated protected swing or order block as the invalidation point.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering before the wick is fully formed and confirmed, such as trading the opposing run in its direction or trying to catch the exact reversal, rather than waiting for price to close back through and establish a protected swing.",
    "Failing to verify that the opposing run has occurred into a relevant point of interest (order block, fair value gap, premium/discount zone) before entering.",
    "Trading inside a candle with a large wick and expecting directional expansion, instead of recognizing it as a reversal candle and waiting for the next higher time frame candle (candle 3) to form a small wick.",
    "Entering without a confirmed change in state of delivery or protected swing to validate the wick completion.",
    "Expecting deep standard deviation or full expansion targets when the candle has already formed a large opposing run; targets should be scaled back toward the daily open."
  ],
